  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What's a good product for Acne?",
  "response": "When seeking effective products for acne, it's essential to choose items based on your skin type and the severity of your acne. Here are some commonly recommended products and ingredients that may help:\n\n1. **Benzoyl Peroxide**: This ingredient helps kill acne-causing bacteria and reduces inflammation. Products like Neutrogena On-the-Spot Acne Treatment or PanOxyl Acne Foaming Wash are popular.\n\n2. **Salicylic Acid**: This beta hydroxy acid helps exfoliate the skin and unclog pores. Look for products like Paula's Choice Skin Perfecting 2% BHA Liquid Exfoliant or Neutrogena Oil-Free Acne Wash.\n\n3. **Retinoids**: Topical retinoids (like adapalene) promote cell turnover and can help prevent clogged pores. Differin Gel (adapalene) is a widely recommended over-the-counter option.\n\n4. **Tea Tree Oil**: This natural antiseptic can be effective for mild acne. Products like The Body Shop Tea Tree Oil The Body Shop Tea Tree Skin Clearing Clay Wash can be helpful.\n\n5. **Niacinamide**: This ingredient can reduce inflammation and improve skin texture. Look for serums or moisturizers that contain niacinamide, such as The Ordinary Niacinamide 10% + Zinc 1%.\n\n6. **Hydrating Products**: Non-comedogenic moisturizers like CeraVe PM Facial Moisturizing Lotion or Neutrogena Hydro Boost Gel may help maintain hydration without clogging pores.\n\n7. **Sulfur**: Sulfur-containing products can help absorb oil and reduce inflammation. Mario Badescu Drying Lotion is a well-known option.\n\n8. **Prescription Treatments**: For moderate to severe acne, consider seeing a dermatologist for prescription medications, which may include topical retinoids, antibiotics, or oral medications like isotretinoin.\n\nAlways perform a patch test when trying new products and consult with a dermatologist for a tailored skincare routine, especially if you're dealing with persistent or severe acne.",
